{"questionId":"35031038","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The diagram shows the straight line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>. Points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math> are points on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/4b9174a40941fe3461f6f292236df56db10b21b1.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext></math> is the midpoint of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AC</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is perpendicular to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> and passes through point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>N</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> is on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the distance between points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>N</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for correctly substituting point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext></math> and their <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>N</mtext></math> into distance formula.</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>24</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>23606</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(A1)</em>(ft)</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Follow through from part (d).</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"35031038","referenceCode":"19N.2.SL.TZ0.T_2e","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the distance between points M and N.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"e","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.1—Equations of straight lines, parallel and perpendicular"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}